# Data Fetching and API Client

## React Query

All client-side data fetching uses **@tanstack/react-query v5** via `useQuery` and `useMutation`.
`QueryProvider` is mounted in `app/layout.tsx` and wraps the entire app.

```tsx
// reads
const { data, isLoading } = useQuery({
  queryKey: ["bank-transactions", filters],
  queryFn: () => listBankTransactions(filters),
});

// writes
const mutation = useMutation({
  mutationFn: (payload) => updateBankTransaction(id, payload),
  onSuccess: () => queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ["bank-transactions"] }),
});
```

- After a mutation succeeds, always call `queryClient.invalidateQueries()` to keep the cache fresh.
- Use `useQueryClient()` to get the client inside components.

## lib/api.ts ‚Äî the single API client

**Every** client-side API call must go through a typed function in `frontend/lib/api.ts`.
Do not call `fetch` directly from components or pages.

The generic wrapper is:
```ts
apiFetch<T>(url: string, schema: ZodType<T>, options?: RequestInit): Promise<T>
```

- Add new domain functions alongside existing ones (e.g., `listBankTransactions`, `getBankTransaction`).
- Response is always validated with `schema.parse(json)` before being returned.
- Query params are appended via `URLSearchParams`.

## Proxy Layer (server-side)

API route handlers in `app/api/` use `lib/proxy.ts` to reach the backend.
These helpers run on the server (they read `process.env.BACKEND_URL`).

```ts
// lib/proxy.ts exports
proxyGet(req)        // GET ‚Äî forwards searchParams
proxyPost(req)       // POST ‚Äî forwards JSON body
proxyPut(req)        // PUT ‚Äî forwards JSON body
proxyPatch(req)      // PATCH ‚Äî forwards JSON body
proxyDelete(req)     // DELETE
```

The backend URL defaults to `http://localhost:8080` if `BACKEND_URL` is unset.
**Never hardcode** `http://localhost:8080` anywhere ‚Äî always read through `backendUrl()`.

## Pagination

- List endpoints use `limit` + `offset` query params.
- Responses conform to `PaginatedResponse<T>`: `{ items, total, limit, offset }`.
- The Zod helper `paginatedSchema<T>(itemSchema)` in `lib/types.ts` builds the list response schema.

## Real-time (Pusher / Soketi)

Long-running operations (receipt OCR, CSV bank import) push progress events via Pusher.

- Subscribe to channels inside `useEffect` using the client from `lib/pusher.ts`.
- Always unsubscribe / unbind in the effect cleanup to avoid memory leaks.
- Progress events update local state (e.g., a progress bar or status message); on completion, call `queryClient.invalidateQueries()` to refresh the list.

```ts
// canonical pattern ‚Äî app/bank-transactions/page.tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const channel = pusherClient.subscribe("import-channel");
  channel.bind("import.progress", handler);
  return () => { channel.unbind_all(); pusherClient.unsubscribe("import-channel"); };
}, []);
```

## Canonical References

- `frontend/lib/api.ts` ‚Äî `apiFetch`, all domain API functions
- `frontend/lib/types.ts` ‚Äî Zod schemas + `paginatedSchema` helper
- `frontend/lib/proxy.ts` ‚Äî `proxyGet` / `proxyPost` / etc.
- `frontend/lib/pusher.ts` ‚Äî Pusher client initialisation
- `frontend/components/QueryProvider.tsx` ‚Äî React Query client setup
- `frontend/app/bank-transactions/page.tsx` ‚Äî Pusher usage + list + mutations
- `frontend/app/bank-transactions/[id]/page.tsx` ‚Äî detail page with multiple mutations
